SIMPLE: fettle
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Fettle
<hw>Fet"tle</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[OE. & Prov. E., to
fettle (in sense 1), <ets>fettle</ets>, <pos>n.</pos>, order, repair,
preparation, dress; prob. akin to E. <ets>fit</ets>. See <er>Fit</er>,
<pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To repair; to prepare; to put in
order.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark> <rj><au>Carlyle.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Metal.)</fld> <def>To cover or line with a mixture
of ore, cinders, etc., as the hearth of a puddling furnace.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fettle</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Fettle
<hw>Fet"tle</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To make preparations; to put
things in order; to do trifling business.</def> <mark>[Prov.
Eng.]</mark> <rj><au>Bp. Hall.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fettle</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Fettle
<hw>Fet"tle</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The act of fettling.</def>
<mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark> <rj><au>Wright.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>In fine fettle</b></col>, <cd>in good
spirits.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fettling</ent>⟦br⟧
